---

## 🔹 4. Token Authentication (Most common)

Step 1 — Login

```http
POST /api/login
```

Body:

```json
{
  "username": "azeez",
  "password": "123"
}
```

Response:

```json
{
  "token": "abc123",
  "role": "FSE"
}
```

Step 2 — Use token

```http
GET /api/devices
Authorization: Bearer abc123
```

Without token:

```
401
```

QA must test this.

---

## 🔹 5. Bearer Token (Most used in REST)

Header format:

```http
Authorization: Bearer <token>
```

Example:

```http
Authorization: Bearer abc123xyz
```

Used in:

* Login session
* Role APIs
* Device APIs
* Config APIs
* Enumerator APIs

Your support tool will use this.

---

## 🔹 6. Role-Based Authentication (Very important for your project)

Login as FSE

Response:

```json
{
  "token": "111",
  "role": "FSE"
}
```

Login as User

```json
{
  "token": "222",
  "role": "USER"
}
```

Call same API

```
GET /features
```

FSE:

```
200 → full features
```

User:

```
403 → limited features
```

QA must test role permission.

Very common in Philips tools.

---

## 🔹 7. Session Authentication (Common in desktop / WPF)

Sometimes token not visible.

Server creates session.

Flow:

```
Login → session id → cookie → next API
```

Header example:

```
Cookie: sessionid=abc123
```

Used in:

* Old tools
* WPF apps
* Internal tools

QA must check session works.

